#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:205
msgid "Real-world cross compiling of a Hello World example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:207
msgid ""
"To show off the power of cross compilation in Nix, let's build our own Hello "
"World program by cross compiling it as static executables to `armv6l-unknown-"
"linux-gnueabihf` and `x86_64-w64-mingw32` (Windows) platforms and run the "
"resulting executable with [an emulator](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/"
"Emulator)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:209
msgid "Given we have a `cross-compile.nix`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:211
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/tarball/"
"release-23.11\";\n"
"  pkgs = import nixpkgs {};\n"
"\n"
"  # Create a C program that prints Hello World\n"
"  helloWorld = pkgs.writeText \"hello.c\" ''\n"
"    #include <stdio.h>\n"
"\n"
"    int main (void)\n"
"    {\n"
"      printf (\"Hello, world!\\n\");\n"
"      return 0;\n"
"    }\n"
"  '';\n"
"\n"
"  # A function that takes host platform packages\n"
"  crossCompileFor = hostPkgs:\n"
"    # Run a simple command with the compiler available\n"
"    hostPkgs.runCommandCC \"hello-world-cross-test\" {} ''\n"
"      # Wine requires home directory\n"
"      HOME=$PWD\n"
"\n"
"      # Compile our example using the compiler specific to our host "
"platform\n"
"      $CC ${helloWorld} -o hello\n"
"\n"
"      # Run the compiled program using user mode emulation (Qemu/Wine)\n"
"      # buildPackages is passed so that emulation is built for the build "
"platform\n"
"      ${hostPkgs.stdenv.hostPlatform.emulator hostPkgs.buildPackages} hello "
"> $out\n"
"\n"
"      # print to stdout\n"
"      cat $out\n"
"    '';\n"
"in {\n"
"  # Statically compile our example using the two platform hosts\n"
"  rpi = crossCompileFor pkgs.pkgsCross.raspberryPi;\n"
"  windows = crossCompileFor pkgs.pkgsCross.mingwW64;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:251
msgid ""
"If we build this example and print both resulting derivations, we should see "
"\"Hello, world!\" for each:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:253
msgid ""
"$ cat $(nix-build cross-compile.nix)\n"
"Hello, world!\n"
"Hello, world!\n"
msgstr ""
"$ cat $(nix-build cross-compile.nix)\n"
"Hello, world!\n"
"Hello, world!\n"

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:259
msgid "Developer environment with a cross compiler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:261
msgid ""
"In the {ref}`tutorial for declarative reproducible environments <declarative-"
"reproducible-envs>`, we looked at how Nix helps us provide tooling and "
"system libraries for our project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:263
msgid ""
"It's also possible to provide an environment with a compiler configured for "
"**cross-compilation to static binaries using musl**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:265
msgid "Given we have a `shell.nix`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:267
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/tarball/"
"release-23.11\";\n"
"  pkgs = (import nixpkgs {}).pkgsCross.aarch64-multiplatform;\n"
"in\n"
"\n"
"# callPackage is needed due to https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/pull/126844\n"
"pkgs.pkgsStatic.callPackage ({ mkShell, zlib, pkg-config, file }: mkShell {\n"
"  # these tools run on the build platform, but are configured to target the "
"host platform\n"
"  nativeBuildInputs = [ pkg-config file ];\n"
"  # libraries needed for the host platform\n"
"  buildInputs = [ zlib ];\n"
"}) {}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:282
msgid "And `hello.c`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:284
msgid ""
"#include <stdio.h>\n"
"\n"
"int main (void)\n"
"{\n"
"  printf (\"Hello, world!\\n\");\n"
"  return 0;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:294
msgid "We can cross compile it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:296
msgid "$ nix-shell --run '$CC hello.c -o hello' shell.nix\n"
msgstr "$ nix-shell --run '$CC hello.c -o hello' shell.nix\n"

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:300
msgid "And confirm it's aarch64:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/cross-compilation.md:302
msgid ""
"$ nix-shell --run 'file hello' shell.nix\n"
"hello: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, ARM aarch64, version 1 (SYSV), statically "
"linked, with debug_info, not stripped\n"
msgstr ""

